Note

Well use the cdc dataset a little longer. As we model this, be sure to try it with the dataset (porche) used in the book

Linear Models (1.1)

Notation

\[Data = Model + Error\] \[Y = f(X) + \epsilon\] \[Y = \mu_Y + \epsilon\] \[\mu_Y = f(X) = \beta_0+\beta_1 X\] \[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \epsilon\]

Making a plot

Well use the ggplot2 package (can also use “base” graphics), use require(ggplot2) and load cdc dataset.

Making a quick plot

qplot(height, weight, data=cdc)

Adding a best-fit line

qplot(height, weight, data=cdc)+geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE)

Method of finding best fit line

  • SSE - sum of squares of the error
  • least sqaures line

Getting the equation for that line

lm(weight~height, data=cdc)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = weight ~ height, data = cdc)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       height  
##    -192.742        5.395

What Residuals Mean

\[y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \epsilon_i\] \[weight_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 * height_i + \epsilon\] \[\widehat{weight} = \beta_0 + \beta_1* height\]
